<paragraph blockId="12.[189,1399,1632,2027]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Swainson" baseAuthorityYear="1825" box="[189,421,1632,1658]" class="Gastropoda" family="Olividae" genus="Amalda" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neogastropoda" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="tankervillii">
<emphasis box="[189,421,1632,1658]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Amalda tankervillii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
occurs in 
<collectingCountry box="[554,675,1632,1658]" name="Venezuela" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Venezuela</collectingCountry>
in shallow water (
<quantity box="[909,1036,1632,1658]" metricMagnitude="1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.8" metricValueMax="7.0" metricValueMin="0.6" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" unit="m" value="38.0" valueMax="70.0" valueMin="6.0">6 to 70 m</quantity>
) and is conchologically quite different from the other species included in the genus (
<figureCitation box="[832,932,1669,1695]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="17.[189,232,1718,1744]" captionTargetBox="[217,1371,265,1690]" captionTargetId="figure@17.[217,1371,265,1690]" captionTargetPageId="17" captionText="Fig. 4. Amalda hilgendorfi (von Martens, 1897). A–D. Typical morph, Japan. A–C. MNHN IM-2019- 616, SL 53.1 mm. D. MNHN IM-2019-621, SL 50.0 mm. E–G. Philippine morph. E. MNHN IM-2007- 31950, SL 38.7 mm. F–G. MNHN IM-2007-33427, SL 40.3 mm. H–L. Solomon Islands and Papua New Guinea (PNG) morph. H. Solomons, MNHN IM-2007-33286, SL 52.6 mm. I. PNG, MNHN IM-2013- 44995, SL 51.3 mm. J. Solomons, MNHN IM-2009-11961, SL 32.9 mm. K. PNG, MNHN IM-2009- 22244, SL 63.1 mm. L. PNG, MNHN IM-2009-23330, SL 69.3 mm. M. Amalda tankervillii (Swainson, 1825), Venezuela, Isla de Margarita, 30–35 m, collection of Ron Voskuil, RV 0175, SL 80 mm. Photo by Ron Voskuil et al. (2011) (http://olivirv.myspecies.info/en/taxon-pages/ancillaria-tankervillii). Shells (except M, reduced) at the same scale." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4010962" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4010962/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Fig. 4M</figureCitation>
). Neither its anatomy nor the molecular data have been examined. Based on shell characters, 
<bibRefCitation author="Voskuil R. P. A." box="[829,1007,1706,1732]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" pagination="49 - 55" refId="ref32127" refString="Voskuil R. P. A. 1991. The recent species of the genus Eburna Lamarck, 1801. Vita Marina 41: 49 - 55." type="journal article" year="1991">Voskuil (1991)</bibRefCitation>
compared 
<taxonomicName authority="Lamarck, 1811" authorityName="Swainson" authorityYear="1825" box="[1141,1399,1706,1732]" class="Gastropoda" family="Ancillariidae" genus="Ancillaria" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neogastropoda" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="tankervillii">
<emphasis box="[1141,1399,1706,1732]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Ancillaria tankervillii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
with species of 
<taxonomicName authority="Lamarck, 1801" authorityName="Lamarck" authorityYear="1801" box="[389,673,1742,1769]" class="Gastropoda" family="Olividae" genus="Eburna" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neogastropoda" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[389,477,1743,1769]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Eburna</emphasis>
Lamarck, 1801
</taxonomicName>
and concluded that 
<taxonomicName authorityName="H. Adams &amp; A. Adams" authorityYear="1853" box="[931,1022,1743,1769]" class="Gastropoda" family="Olividae" genus="Amalda" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neogastropoda" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus" sensu="stricto">
<emphasis box="[931,1022,1743,1769]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Amalda</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1035,1102,1743,1769]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" sensu="stricto">s. str.</taxonomicNameLabel>
should be considered a subgenus of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lamarck" authorityYear="1801" box="[344,432,1779,1805]" class="Gastropoda" family="Olividae" genus="Eburna" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neogastropoda" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[344,432,1779,1805]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Eburna</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, while the Indo-Pacific species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="H. Adams &amp; A. Adams" authorityYear="1853" box="[858,949,1779,1805]" class="Gastropoda" family="Olividae" genus="Amalda" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neogastropoda" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[858,949,1779,1805]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Amalda</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
probably belong to a separate genus 
<taxonomicName authority="P. Fischer, 1883" authorityName="P. Fischer" authorityYear="1883" box="[189,514,1816,1843]" class="Gastropoda" family="Olividae" genus="Baryspira" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neogastropoda" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[189,306,1817,1842]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Baryspira</emphasis>
P. Fischer, 1883
</taxonomicName>
. Although 
<taxonomicName authority="Lamarck, 1811" authorityName="Swainson" authorityYear="1825" box="[650,815,1816,1843]" class="Gastropoda" family="Ancillariidae" genus="Ancillaria" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neogastropoda" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="tankervillii">
<emphasis box="[650,815,1816,1843]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">A. tankervillii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is indeed somewhat different from Indo-Pacific species in being thin, broadly oval, with a large inflated last whorl and a very low spire, in the absence of molecular and anatomical data the opinion of 
<bibRefCitation author="Voskuil R. P. A." box="[758,933,1890,1916]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" pagination="49 - 55" refId="ref32127" refString="Voskuil R. P. A. 1991. The recent species of the genus Eburna Lamarck, 1801. Vita Marina 41: 49 - 55." type="journal article" year="1991">Voskuil (1991)</bibRefCitation>
remains speculative. Herein, we follow the generally accepted taxonomic concept of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="H. Adams &amp; A. Adams" authorityYear="1853" box="[715,806,1927,1953]" class="Gastropoda" family="Olividae" genus="Amalda" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neogastropoda" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[715,806,1927,1953]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Amalda</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and do not attempt to revise its generic/subgeneric structure, which will require a much broader molecular taxon sampling than is currently available, as well, as sequencing additional genetic markers.
</paragraph>
